{{for|the fictional FBI agent|List of The Mentalist characters#Recurring characters}} {{Infobox aviator | name = Susan Darcy | image = | image_size = | alt = | caption = | full_name = | birth_name = | birth_date = {{Birth year and age|1956}} | birth_place = | death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> | death_place = | death_cause = | resting_place = | resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LATITUDE|LONGITUDE|type:landmark}} --> | monuments = | nationality = American | education = [[University of Washington]] | spouse = | relatives = | known_for = [[Boeing]]'s first female [[test pilot]] | first_flight_date = | first_flight_aircraft = | famous_flights = | license_date = | license_place = | rank = Captain | awards = | memorials = | website = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} --> | child = | module = }} '''Susan Darcy''' (born 1956) was the first female [[test pilot]] for the [[Boeing]] company. Initially an assistant engineer for the company, she progressed to an instructor role and then a test pilot for a wide range of aircraft.
==Career== Susan Darcy was born in 1956. She joined the [[Boeing]] company in 1974 as an assistant engineer, but was inspired to fly and began to take lessons in 1977. Around the same time, she attended the [[University of Washington]] to study aeronautics and astronautics, graduating with a [[Bachelor of Science]] degree in 1981. The following year, she was promoted at Boeing to an instructor in the training department. This job involved training pilots in how the aeroplanes functioned and writing parts of the operations manuals.<ref name="welch">{{cite book|last1=Welch|first1=Rosanne|title=Encyclopedia of Women in Aviation and Space|date=1998|publisher=ABC-CLIO|location=Santa Barbara, Calif|isbn=978-0-874369-588|pages=53–54}}</ref>
She was promoted to a [[test pilot]] position on October 31, 1985. This made her the first female test pilot employed by the company.<ref name="welch"/> In 1986, she was one of the speakers at the first World Aviation Education and Safety Congress, held in [[New Delhi]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Hollander|first1=Lu|last2=Jessen|first2=Gene Nora|last3=West|first3=Verna|title=The Ninety-Nines: Yesterday-Today-Tomorrow|date=1996|publisher=Turner Pub. Co.|location=Paducah, Ky.|isbn=978-1-563112-034|page=40|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=tfZBKREXdjgC&pg=PA40}}</ref> Over the next three years, Darcy accrued accreditation on the [[Boeing 737]], [[Boeing 757|757]] and [[Boeing 767|767]]. When she was accredited for the [[Boeing 747-400]] in 1989, she was the first woman to Captain that type of plane. Her job also involved testing prototype planes, and on occasion, flying them to overseas buyers.<ref name="welch"/> By 1991, she remained one of two female test pilots for Boeing, alongside [[Rose Looper]] who joined shortly after her.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Mikell|first1=Ann|title=Sky Is The Limit For Test Pilot|url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/1991-08-21/news/9108210497_1_test-pilot-loper-flight-test|accessdate=November 19, 2017|work=Orlando Sentinel|date=August 21, 1991}}</ref> She was part of the promotional Asian tour of the [[Boeing 777]] in 1995, and was part of the team who flew a plane from [[Bangkok]], [[Thailand]], to [[Seattle]] in a world record time.<ref>{{cite news|title=Boeing 777 sets World Record from Bangkok to Seattle|url=https://www.thefreelibrary.com/BOEING+777+SETS+WORLD+SPEED+RECORD+FROM+BANGKOK+TO+SEATTLE-a016876428|accessdate=November 19, 2017|work=PR Newswire|publisher=TheFreeLibrary|date=April 30, 1995}}</ref>
