{{Refimprove|date=October 2017}}
'''Trade Unions''' play a major role in the [[corporatist]] '''[[Dutch economy]]'''.

== Dynamics ==
In 2001 about 25% of the Dutch people who were employed were organized in a union. There are three major unions: the [[Christian-democracy in the Netherlands|Christian-democratic]] "[[Christelijk Nationaal Vakverbond|Christelijk Nationaal Vakverbond (CNV)]]", the [[social democracy in the Netherlands|social-democratically oriented]] "[[Federatie Nederlandse Vakbeweging|Federatie Nederlandse Vakbeweging (FNV)]]" and the "[[Federation of Managerial and Professional Staff Unions|Federation of Managerial and Professional Staff Unions (MHP)]]". All are federations of sector-based labour unions. The FNV is with about 1,4 million members<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fnv.nl/publiek/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-10-24 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101023124053/http://www.fnv.nl/publiek/ |archivedate=2010-10-23 |df= }} </ref> the largest of the three. The CNV has 350.000<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnv.nl/speciaal/english/|title=English|website=Cnv.nl|accessdate=5 October 2017}}</ref> members and the MHP 160.000.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vakcentralemhp.nl/organisatie.asp |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-10-24 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130222175122/http://www.vakcentralemhp.nl/organisatie.asp |archivedate=2013-02-22 |df= }} </ref> The FNV has 17 affiliate unions, the CNV 11 and the MHP 4. 

The labour unions play a major role in the [[Economy of the Netherlands|Dutch economy]] because, first, they bargain with [[employers' organizations]] over wages and working conditions (these deals are binding for all employed people), and second, they advise the government on economic legislation through its membership of the [[Social-Economic Council|Social-Economic Council (SER)]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ser.nl/en/about_the_ser/members.aspx|title=Members of the SER - SER|website=Ser.nl|accessdate=5 October 2017}}</ref>

Traditionally Dutch labour unions were part of the [[pillarization|pillarized structure of society]]. Each social group had a pillar: the [[Protestantism in the Netherlands|Protestants]] (CNV), the [[Catholicism in the Netherlands|Catholics]] ([[NKV]], merged into FNV), the social-democrats ([[Nederlands Verbond van Vakverenigingen|NVV]], merged into FNV) and the syndicalists ([[National Labor Secretariat|NAS]]).

